elements.content: Solvothermal reactions of V-shaped ligand 1,1′-(oxybis­(1,4-phenylene))-bis­(1H-1,2,4-triazole) (OPBT) with deprotonated phthalic acid (H2PA) or (1,1′-biphenyl)-4,4′-dicarboxylic acid (H2BDA) in the presence of transition metal nitrates in N,N-dimethylformamide/water (DMF/H2O) solvent system yielded five new complexes: [Cu5(μ3-OH)2(OPBT)2(PA)4] n (1), [Cd2(OPBT)­(PA)2] n (2), {[Zn­(OPBT)­(PA)]·H2O} n (3), [Cd­(μ2-H2O)­(OPBT)­(BDA)] n (4), and [Co­(OPBT)2(BDA)] n (5). Complexes 1 and 2 show two-dimensional (2D) layers based on one-dimensional (1D) infinite rod second building units (SBUs) of pentanuclear Cu­(II) or tetranuclear Cd­(II) clusters with OPBT ligands, which are further formed into three-dimensional (3D) supramolecular frameworks by interlayer hydrogen bonding or π···π stacking interactions, respectively. Complex 3 displays a 1D chain, which is further extended into a 3D supramolecular structure through C–H···π and hydrogen bonding interactions. Complex 4 features a 2D layer with the sql topology, which is further formed into a 3D supramolecular framework by interlayer hydrogen bonds. Complex 5 possesses a 2D 2-fold interpenetrating polyrotaxane structure (2D + 2D → 2D) with the sql topology, which is further extended into a 3D supramolecular framework through interlayer π···π stacking interactions. Furthermore, photoluminescent spectra of complexes 2–4 and UV–visible spectra of complex 5 have been studied. Subsequently, mesoporous Co3O4 is obtained by calcination of complex 5. The as-made mesoporous Co3O4 is investigated for its application as supercapacitor electrode and energy storage material in 1, 2, and 3 M KOH electrolytes, respectively. The electrochemical analyses show that mesoporous Co3O4 exhibits a relatively higher specific capacitance of 285.4 F g–1 at the current density of 0.5 A g–1 and retains 87% at 3 A g–1 after 3000 cycles in 3 M KOH electrolyte. The results demonstrate that mesoporous Co3O4 with specific morphology can act as a promising electrode candidate in supercapacitors.

elements.content: Metal–organic frameworks (MOFs) are constructed by the self-assembly of metal ions/metal-containing clusters and organic bridging units. Because of the richness and diversity of metal ions/metal-containing clusters and organic bridging units, there are more than twenty thousand different MOFs designed and studied over the last 20 years, which exhibit rich structure types and intriguing properties and functions. Among them, much effort has been devoted to constructing MOFs in combination with carboxylates and N-donor ligands and exploring their practical applications. These N-donor ligands such as pyridines, imidazoles, triazoles, tetrazoles, and their derivates have been used in the synthesis of unique MOFs that possess excellent coordination ability. However, the design and synthesis of new coordination polymers based on triazole ligands are still a long-standing pursuit of chemists. To date, coordination polymers based on the V-shaped OPBT ligands are rarely investigated. In particular, the OPBT contains 1,2,4-triazoles, which combine the coordination geometry of both imidazoles and pyrazoles to arrange their three heteroatoms and may provide not only more coordination sites but also more hydrogen bond acceptors compared to similar pyridine and imidazole ligands. So herein we employ the OPBT ligand to prepare five new complexes [Cu5(μ3-OH)2(OPBT)2(PA)4] n (1), [Cd2(OPBT)­(PA)2] n (2), {[Zn­(OPBT)­(PA)]·H2O} n (3), [Cd­(μ2-H2O)­(OPBT)­(BDA)] n (4), and [Co­(OPBT)2(BDA)] n (5) with auxiliary H2PA or H2BDA () as well as different transition metal ions. Their crystal structures have been characterized by single crystal X-ray diffraction analysis, infrared spectroscopy, elemental analysis, powder X-ray diffraction, and thermogravimetric analysis. The photoluminescent properties of complexes 2–4 and UV–visible spectra of complex 5 are also discussed in detail.

Introduction

Metal-organic frameworks (MOFs) are constructed by the self-assembly of metal ions/metal-containing clusters and organic bridging units. Because of the richness and diversity of metal ions/metal-containing clusters and organic bridging units, there are more than twenty thousand different MOFs designed and studied over the last 20 years, which exhibit rich structure types and intriguing properties and functions. Among them, much effort has been devoted to constructing MOFs in combination with carboxylates and N-donor ligands and exploring their practical applications. These N-donor ligands such as pyridines, imidazoles, triazoles, tetrazoles, and their derivates have been used in the synthesis of unique MOFs that possess excellent coordination ability. However, the design and synthesis of new coordination polymers based on triazole ligands are still a long-standing pursuit of chemists. To date, coordination polymers based on the V-shaped OPBT ligands are rarely investigated. In particular, the OPBT contains 1,2,4-triazoles, which combine the coordination geometry of both imidazoles and pyrazoles to arrange their three heteroatoms and may provide not only more coordination sites but also more hydrogen bond acceptors compared to similar pyridine and imidazole ligands. So herein we employ the OPBT ligand to prepare five new complexes [Cu5(μ3-OH)2(OPBT)2(PA)4] n  (1), [Cd2(OPBT)(PA)2] n  (2), {[Zn(OPBT)(PA)]⋅H2O} n  (3), [Cd(μ2-H2O)(OPBT)(BDA)] n  (4), and [Co(OPBT)2(BDA)] n  (5) with auxiliary H2PA or H2BDA () as well as different transition metal ions. Their crystal structures have been characterized by single crystal X-ray diffraction analysis, infrared spectroscopy, elemental analysis, powder X-ray diffraction, and thermogravimetric analysis. The photoluminescent properties of complexes 2-4 and UV-visible spectra of complex 5 are also discussed in detail.

elements.content: Notably, some MOF crystals as precursors have been utilized to generate porous metal oxide nanomaterials with specific morphologies through simple solid-state thermolysis strategy. Among transitions metal oxides, nanostructural Co3O4 is one of the ideal and promising electrode materials for electrochemical pseudosupercapacitors because of relatively low cost, high theoretic specific capacitance (3560 F g–1), and low environmental footprint. According to the mechanism that dictates the performance of supercapacitors, it is critical to control the structures of electrode materials to improve the ability of electron transportation and ion diffusion. Recently, Co3O4 nanostructures with different morphologies (such as nanotubes, nanosheets, nanoparticles, microspindle, microflowers, nanorods, hollow decahedrons, dendrite-like nanostructure, and so on) have been produced by calcining the precursors Co-MOFs and utilized to construct high-performance supercapacitors. For instance, Wang et al. prepared porous Co3O4 nanotubes derived from Co-MOF-74 as high performance supercapacitor electrodes, which display a specific capacitance of 647 F g–1 at a current density of 1 A g–1. Despite many efforts that have been devoted to synthesizing nanostructure Co3O4 electrode materials for supercapacitors, it has a great challenge to design and synthesize precursors and maintain the specific morphologies after further calcinations.

The dinuclear Zn­(II) clusters in complex 3 are bridged by μ2-bridged OPBT ligands to generate 1D chains. In the complexes 4 and 5, the Cd­(II) and Co­(II) ions are bridged by terminal and μ2-bridged OPBT ligands, respectively. Furthermore, their structures are extended into the resulting 3D supramolecular frameworks by C–H···π, π···π stacking, or hydrogen bonding interaction as shown in .

elements.content: To examine the thermal stabilities of complexes 1–5, thermogravimetric (TG) analyses were carried out (). The TG curves indicate that complexes 1, 2, and 5 begin to collapse at 250, 325, and 355 °C, respectively, which indicate that complex 5 has relatively higher thermal stability. For complex 3, there is a weight loss of approximately 3.23% from room temperature to 135 °C, corresponding to the loss of one lattice water molecule (3.26% calcd). Then TG curve presents a platform until approximately 295 °C. Finally, rapid weight losses are observed, which are attributed to the decomposition of coordination frameworks for complex 3. The TG study of complex 4 shows a weight loss of 2.75% (calc. 2.67%) from room temperature to 100 °C, suggesting that one μ2-H2O molecule is removed. Then there is a slow weight loss and no obvious platform until approximately 360 °C, proving that the initial structure has not been maintained. Later, a rapid weight loss suggests that the decomposition of the structure begins to collapse.

elements.content: Complexes especially with d10 metal centers have been investigated for photoluminescent properties due to their potential applications as luminescent materials. The solid-state photoluminescence of organic ligands and complexes 2–4 are determined at room temperature, as shown in and Table S3. Upon excitation at ca. 324 nm for OPBT, 313 nm for H2PA, and 313 nm for H2BDA, the emissions show at ca. 384 nm for OPBT, 380 and 415 nm for H2PA, and 427 nm for H2BDA, respectively, which can be assigned to the π* → π or π* → n electronic transitions. The absorption peaks at 263 and 299 nm for OPBT, 319 nm for H2BDA, which can be ascribed to π → π* or n → π* transitions of these ligands, respectively. We observe that complex 5 has the similar higher energy bands of 320 nm, which is considered as intraligand charge transfer transitions. Moreover, we also observe the absorption peak at 491 nm for complex 5, which can be assigned to the 4T1g(F) → 4T1g(P) transitions. To explore the semiconductivity, the diffuse reflectance data is transformed into Kubelka–Munk function to obtain their band gaps (E g). elements.content: Based on the TG result, the resultant Co3O4 material could be prepared by calcination of complex 5 at 500 °C. Accordingly, the PXRD pattern of the as-prepared sample is then performed, and the diffraction peaks match well with that of face-centered cubic (fcc) phase Co3O4 (JCPDS card no. 43-1003) in Figure S16. The red crystal 5 has the slate-like shape under the microscope, and the morphology of its pyrolysis product Co3O4 displays irregular sheet-like nanoporous structure using the scanning electron microscopy (SEM) in Figure S17. To gain further insight into the porous feature of the as-prepared Co3O4 material, the N2 adsorption–desorption isotherm at 77 K and the Barrett–Joyner–Halenda (BJH) adsorption pore size distribution plot of the Co3O4 are shown in Figure S18. It is observed that the N2 adsorption isotherm is a typical IV type curve, and the hysteresis loop further suggests its mesoporous structure. The specific Brunauer–Emmett–Teller (BET) surface area of the Co3O4 is measured to be 6.79 m2 g–1. Additionally, according to the corresponding Barrett–Joyner–Halenda (BJH) pore size distribution curve, the average pore size is measured to be about 30 nm (inset in Figure S18).

elements.content: The electrochemical performances of the mesoporous Co3O4 electrode materials were investigated by CV and CP testing in a three-electrode beaker cell in different concentrations of KOH electrolytes. a, S19a, and S19b show the representative CV curves of the Co3O4 electrode at various scan rates from 5 to 200 mV s–1 in 3, 2, and 1 M KOH electrolytes, respectively. The curves show that two pair of redox peaks correspond to the reversible conversion between different cobalt oxidation states within the range 0.1–0.5 V (Figure S20). This suggests that the measured capacitance of the Co3O4 electrode mainly results from the pseudocapacitance behavior due to two faradic redox reactions listed as follows: Co 3 O 4 + OH − + H 2 O ↔ 3 CoOOH + e − CoOOH + OH − ↔ Co O 2 + H 2 O + e − wherein the peak current increases with an increase in the scan rate and in the electrolyte concentration, indicating rapid electronic and ionic transport processes, which are beneficial to the fast charge–discharge performance. However, the slight redox peak shift is attributed to the polarization effect of the electrode.

elements.content: To further evaluate the application potential of the as-made Co3O4 materials as electrodes for electrochemical capacitors, CP tests were carried out in 3, 2, and 1 M KOH electrolytes between 0 and 0.4 V (vs standard calomel electrode (SCE)) at various current densities ranging from 0.5 to 5 A g–1, as shown in b, S19c, and S19d. The specific capacitances of the electrode at different current densities can be calculated by using the following equation: C = I Δ t / ( m Δ V ) where C (F g–1) is the specific capacitance, I (A) is the discharge current, Δt (s) is the total discharge time, m (g) represents the mass of Co3O4 within the composite electrodes, and ΔV (V) is the potential drop during discharge. As a result, the specific capacitance values of the Co3O4 electrode (c) were calculated to be 285.4, 263.3, 241.0, 227.3, and 217.5 F g–1 at current densities of 0.5, 1, 2, 3, and 5 A g–1 in 3 M KOH electrolyte, respectively. The corresponding specific capacitance values were 284.1, 256.0, 223.5, 200.3, and 181.3 F g–1 in 2 M KOH electrolyte, and 272.0, 243.0, 214.5, 196.5, and 176.3 F g–1 in 1 M KOH electrolyte, respectively. These specific capacitance values of mesoporous Co3O4 materials are much higher than that of commercial Co3O4 electrode, which is 77 F g–1. The capacitance of Co3O4 electrodes exhibit 76.2%, 63.8%, and 64.8% retention from 0.5 to 5 A g–1 in 3, 2, and 1 M KOH electrolytes, respectively, indicating the good rate capability of mesoporous Co3O4 electrode. It was observed that the capacitances decreased with an increase in discharge current density, which can be attributed the relatively insufficient faradic reactions at higher current densities.

Conclusions

In summary, we successfully synthesized five new Cu(II)/Cd(II)/Zn(II)/Co(II) complexes, which were constructed from a V-shaped OPBT ligand with aromatic dicarboxylate ligands under hydrothermal conditions. Their 1D or 2D structures are extended into the resulting 3D supramolecular structures by C-H⋅⋅⋅π, π⋅⋅⋅π stacking, or hydrogen bonding interactions. Furthermore, photoluminescent spectra of complexes 2-4 suggest that they may be candidates as photoluminescent materials. The as-prepared mesoporous Co3O4 electrode from complex 5 can be applied as an electrode material for supercapacitor, and it could deliver a maximum specific capacitance of 285.4 F g-1 at 0.5 A g-1 and displays excellent recycling stability after 3000 cycles at 3 A g-1 in 3 M KOH electrolyte. Furthermore, the facile approach by calcination of MOFs can be easily extended to prepare other porous metal oxide-based electrode materials with well-defined morphologies in supercapacitors.

In this article, mesoporous Co3O4 is prepared by further calcining new complex 5 with two-dimensional (2D) 2-fold interpenetrating polyrotaxane structure. The electrochemical properties of the Co3O4 electrodes are investigated through cyclic voltammetry (CV) and chronopotentiometry (CP) measurements in 1, 2, and 3 M KOH electrolytes, respectively. The electrochemical analyses show that the Co3O4 materials exhibit a specific capacitance of 285.4 F g–1 at the current density of 0.5 A g–1 and retain 87% after 3000 cycles in 3 M KOH electrolyte, suggesting their potential applications as electrode materials for supercapacitors.

[Cd<sub>2</sub>(OPBT)­(PA)<sub>2</sub>]<sub> <italic>n</italic> </sub> (<bold>2</bold>)

Complex 2 also crystallizes the same triclinic crystal system of space group P1̅ as 1. The asymmetric unit contains two crystallographic-independent Cd­(II) ions, one OPBT ligand, and two deprotonated H2PA ligands. Both crystallographic independent Cd­(II) atoms are six-coordinated with distorted octahedral {CdNO5} environments, which are coordinated by five oxygen atoms from four PA2– ligands and one nitrogen atom from one OPBT ligand (Figure S3). The Cd–N distances are 2.295(3) and 2.336(3) Å, and the Cd–O distances range from 2.227(2) to 2.602(2) Å. As shown in a, there is a tetranuclear Cd­(II) cluster motif, which is bridged by 10 carboxylic groups from eight PA2– ligands. The tetranuclear Cd­(II) cluster is composed of a parallelogram arrangement of four coplanar Cd­(II) ions (Cd1, Cd1#6, Cd2#1 and Cd2#5, #1 = x – 1, y, z; #5 = −x, −y, −z + 2; #6 = −x – 1, −y, −z + 2). The short edge (Cd1···Cd2#5) of the parallelogram is 3.9637(5) Å, and the long edge (Cd1···Cd2#1) is 4.0880(6) Å. The short diagonal (Cd2#1···Cd1#5) of the parallelogram is 3.8192(5) Å, and the long diagonal (Cd1···Cd1#6) is 7.0893 Å.

{[Zn­(OPBT)­(PA)]·H<sub>2</sub>O}<sub> <italic>n</italic> </sub> (<bold>3</bold>)

Complex 3 crystallizes the triclinic crystal system of space group P1̅. The asymmetric unit consists of one Zn­(II) ion, one OPBT ligand, one deprotonated H2PA ligand, and one lattice water molecule. As shown in a, each Zn­(II) ion shows a slightly distorted {ZnN2O2} tetrahedral coordination geometry, which is four-coordinated by two carboxylate oxygen atoms from two PA2– ligands and two nitrogen atoms from two OPBT ligands. The Zn–O bond lengths are 1.9330(17) and 1.9433(18) Å, and the Zn–N ones are 2.025(2) Å.

[Cd­(μ<sub>2</sub>-H<sub>2</sub>O)­(OPBT)­(BDA)]<sub> <italic>n</italic> </sub> (<bold>4</bold>)

Crystal structure determination reveals that complex 4 crystallizes in the monoclinic crystal system of C2/c space group. In the asymmetric unit, it contains a Cd­(II) cation, a μ2-H2O molecule, a OPBT ligand, and a BDA2– anion. As shown in a, each Cd­(II) ion is seven-coordinated with a slightly distorted {CdNO6} pentagonal bipyramid coordination geometry, which is coordinated by one nitrogen atom from one OPBT ligand, six oxygen atoms from two coordinated μ2-H2O molecules and two deprotonated BDA2– ligands at the axial positions with the O­(1W)–Cd(1)–N(1) angles of 165.81(7)°. The Cd–N bond length is 2.261(2) Å, and the Cd–O bond lengths range from 2.2788(17) to 2.5148(17) Å.

To examine the thermal stabilities of complexes 1–5, thermogravimetric (TG) analyses were carried out (). The TG curves indicate that complexes 1, 2, and 5 begin to collapse at 250, 325, and 355 °C, respectively, which indicate that complex 5 has relatively higher thermal stability. For complex 3, there is a weight loss of approximately 3.23% from room temperature to 135 °C, corresponding to the loss of one lattice water molecule (3.26% calcd). Then TG curve presents a platform until approximately 295 °C. Finally, rapid weight losses are observed, which are attributed to the decomposition of coordination frameworks for complex 3. The TG study of complex 4 shows a weight loss of 2.75% (calc. 2.67%) from room temperature to 100 °C, suggesting that one μ2-H2O molecule is removed. Then there is a slow weight loss and no obvious platform until approximately 360 °C, proving that the initial structure has not been maintained. Later, a rapid weight loss suggests that the decomposition of the structure begins to collapse.

Photoluminescent Properties

Complexes especially with d10 metal centers have been investigated for photoluminescent properties due to their potential applications as luminescent materials. The solid-state photoluminescence of organic ligands and complexes 2–4 are determined at room temperature, as shown in and Table S3. Upon excitation at ca. 324 nm for OPBT, 313 nm for H2PA, and 313 nm for H2BDA, the emissions show at ca. 384 nm for OPBT, 380 and 415 nm for H2PA, and 427 nm for H2BDA, respectively, which can be assigned to the π* → π or π* → n electronic transitions. The emission peaks were at 396 nm (λex = 335 nm), 400 nm (λex = 353 nm), and 417 nm (λex = 350 nm) for complex 2–4, respectively. In comparison with the OPBT ligand, the emission maxima of complexes 2–4 are red-shifted, which should be assigned to the intraligand charge transfer because of the Zn­(II) and Cd­(II) ions are difficultly oxidized or reduced. Furthermore, the emission decay lifetimes of complexes 2–4 were measured, and the curves (Figures S11–S13) are best fitted by biexponentials in the solid. The emission decay lifetimes are τ1 = 1.15 μs (48.94%), τ2 = 8.78 μs (51.06%) (χ2 = 1.067) for complex 2, τ1 = 2.13 μs (11.03%), τ2 = 10.27 μs (88.97%) (χ2 = 1.105) for complex 3, and τ1 = 1.13 μs (40.09%), τ2 = 9.67 μs (59.91%) (χ2 = 1.389) for complex 4.

UV–vis Absorption Spectra

The solid-state UV–vis absorption spectra of OPBT ligand, H2BDA ligand, and complex 5 were carried out at room temperature as shown in the Figure S14. The absorption peaks at 263 and 299 nm for OPBT, 319 nm for H2BDA, which can be ascribed to π → π* or n → π* transitions of these ligands, respectively. We observe that complex 5 has the similar higher energy bands of 320 nm, which is considered as intraligand charge transfer transitions. Moreover, we also observe the absorption peak at 491 nm for complex 5, which can be assigned to the 4T1g(F) → 4T1g(P) transitions. To explore the semiconductivity, the diffuse reflectance data is transformed into Kubelka–Munk function to obtain their band gaps (E g). As shown in Figure S15, the band gap of OPBT and H2BDA are approximately 3.18 and 3.23 eV, respectively, which exhibit the nature of semiconductivity. The E g values of complex 5 assessed from the steep absorption edges are 1.95 and 2.68 eV, which are estimated to be greater than the semiconductor silicon material with a band gap of 1.1 eV and indicates that complex 5 is a potential wide band gap semiconductor material.

Electrochemical Analysis

Based on the TG result, the resultant Co3O4 material could be prepared by calcination of complex 5 at 500 °C. Accordingly, the PXRD pattern of the as-prepared sample is then performed, and the diffraction peaks match well with that of face-centered cubic (fcc) phase Co3O4 (JCPDS card no. 43-1003) in Figure S16. The red crystal 5 has the slate-like shape under the microscope, and the morphology of its pyrolysis product Co3O4 displays irregular sheet-like nanoporous structure using the scanning electron microscopy (SEM) in Figure S17. To gain further insight into the porous feature of the as-prepared Co3O4 material, the N2 adsorption–desorption isotherm at 77 K and the Barrett–Joyner–Halenda (BJH) adsorption pore size distribution plot of the Co3O4 are shown in Figure S18. It is observed that the N2 adsorption isotherm is a typical IV type curve, and the hysteresis loop further suggests its mesoporous structure. The specific Brunauer–Emmett–Teller (BET) surface area of the Co3O4 is measured to be 6.79 m2 g–1. Additionally, according to the corresponding Barrett–Joyner–Halenda (BJH) pore size distribution curve, the average pore size is measured to be about 30 nm (inset in Figure S18).
